column1: Rule 1: Modifiers containing an aromatic carboxylic acid group with additional electron-donating groups such as amino or hydroxyl groups tend to result in a high yield.
column2: Rule 2: Modifiers with amino acids or derivatives, especially those with aromatic side chains or additional functional groups like indole, tend to result in a high yield.
column3: Rule 3: Modifiers containing a sulfanyl group (thiol) tend to result in a high yield.
column4: Rule 4: Modifiers with multiple hydroxyl groups, such as polyols, tend to result in a high yield.
column5: Rule 5: Modifiers with electron-withdrawing groups such as nitro groups on an aromatic ring tend to result in a high yield.
column6: Rule 6: Modifiers with long aliphatic chains without additional functional groups tend to result in a low yield.
column7: Rule 7: Modifiers with ether linkages and no additional coordinating groups tend to result in a low yield.
column8: Rule 8: Modifiers with a high degree of fluorination tend to result in a low yield.
column9: Rule 9: Modifiers with ketone groups on an aliphatic chain tend to result in a low yield.
column10: Rule 10: Modifiers with pyridine rings without additional functional groups tend to result in a low yield.
column11: Rule 11: Modifiers with formyl groups on an aromatic ring tend to result in a low yield.
column12: Rule 12: Modifiers with both aromatic and aliphatic carboxylic acid groups, especially when combined with electron-donating groups, tend to result in a high yield.
column13: Rule 13: Modifiers with a combination of aromatic rings and sulfanyl groups tend to result in a high yield.
column14: Rule 14: Modifiers with a pyridine ring and an additional carboxylic acid group tend to result in a high yield.
column15: Rule 15: Modifiers with a benzofuran structure and additional carboxylic acid groups tend to result in a high yield.
